<center>
<h2>The <i>Chicago Tribune</i></h2>
</center>

<center>1885: February 3</center>

<br>
<center><b>Twain and Cable.</b></center>

<p>A large audience again met George W. Cable and Mark Twain at
Central Music Hall last night, leaving only a few seats vacant on
the outskirts of the hall. Mr. Cable's recitations again received
intelligent and smiling consideration, while Mr. Clemens convulsed
the house with uncontrollable mirth. His account of the runaway
slave's escape from the log cabin under the auspices of Tom Sawyer
and Huckleberry Finn was irresistible. There will be another
reading tonight.</p>

